				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">As Oil Prices Go, So Go Financial Markets?</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Teresa Tritch			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-10-23T13:53:56+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 23, 2015 9:53 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 23, 2015 9:53 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/10/23/as-oil-prices-go-so-go-financial-markets/" data-title="As Oil Prices Go, So Go Financial Markets?" data-description="Stock sales by oil-rich nations are a reminder that some state-run funds are far from transparent about their holdings.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/22/opinion/22tritchWEB2/22tritchWEB2-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/22/opinion/22tritchWEB2/22tritchWEB2-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/22/opinion/22tritchWEB2/22tritchWEB2-blog480.jpg" id="100000003993446" width="480" height="274" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="274"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> LM Otero/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In recent months, low oil prices and volatile stock prices have led some oil rich nations to sell stocks to raise cash and reduce the riskiness of their holdings. <a href="//www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/8f2eb94c-62ac-11e5-a28b-50226830d644.html#axzz3pJi0YtYo">According to the Financial Times</a>, redemptions from Saudi Arabia totaling an estimated $50 billion to $70 billion (and possibly more) caught some asset management firms off guard last month, with one describing a day of large Saudi withdrawals as âour black Monday.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But for all the danger implied by that phrase, little is known about potential risks in the changing size and mix of foreign reserves and other investments from state-run funds that manage sovereign wealth.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Unexpected transactions are a reminder that many sovereign wealth funds are secretive about their holdings and strategies. This opacity is a problem because it can breed and amplify volatility, but it persists despite international efforts by finance officials and investor groups to create rules on transparency. Persian Gulf funds, in particular, which hold about one fourth of the roughly $7 trillion in sovereign wealth funds, tend to be opaque. In a <a href="//www.piie.com/publications/pb/pb13-19.pdf">ranking</a> of transparency and accountability compiled by Edwin Truman, a senior fellow at the Peterson Institute for International Economics, funds in Qatar, Oman and Brunei are near the bottom, as are two of several funds from the United Arab Emirates. Even the sovereign wealth fund of Kuwait, which has the highest rank among its Middle East peers, is less transparent than funds in Norway (which tops the list), Australia, Canada, Singapore and seven other countries.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The pressures on oil rich nations are also a reminder that large asset managers with ties to sovereign funds â including BlackRock, the worldâs largest asset manager â are not regulated as âsystemically important financial institutionsâ or âsifis.â The sifi designation, imposed by financial regulators, means that an institution would likely pose a threat to the financial system if it were to founder. Accordingly, sifis â which include the worldâs biggest banks â are held to higher regulatory standards than non-sifis.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Regulators decided not to treat large asset management firms as sifis after considerable debate and after vigorous lobbying by firms that were eager to avoid heightened regulation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Did regulators make the right call? Perhaps. But it is hard to be sanguine as huge and often secretive sovereign investors interact with huge and relatively unregulated asset managers in an unusual global context of <a href="//www.nasdaq.com/markets/crude-oil-brent.aspx?timeframe=1y">prolonged low oil prices</a>. A lesson of the financial crisis is that interconnections among financial players that are stable in one context can become unstable as circumstances change.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Do regulators understand the linkages â financial and economic â that will be tested if oil prices remain low or fall further? Reassurances are few and risks are many.</p>
	</div>
